{
  "Which statement about the rock cycle is true?": "",
  "Any rock type can transform into any other type": "",
  "It always starts with igneous rocks": "",
  "Sedimentary rocks cannot become igneous": "",
  "Metamorphic rocks can only become sedimentary": "",
  "The rock cycle has no fixed starting point; any rock type can be transformed into any other through the appropriate geological processes such as melting, weathering, or heat and pressure.": "",
  "The rock cycle is driven by:": "",
  "Only Earth's internal heat": "",
  "Only the Sun": "",
  "Lunar gravity alone": "",
  "Both Earth's internal heat and solar energy": "",
  "Internal heat drives plate tectonics, volcanism, and metamorphism, while solar energy drives weathering, erosion, and the water cycle, and together they power all processes in the rock cycle.": "",
  "Weathering and erosion break down any rock into:": "",
  "Igneous rock directly": "",
  "Sediments": "",
  "Magma": "",
  "Metamorphic rock": "",
  "Weathering and erosion break rocks into smaller fragments called sediments, which can then be transported, deposited, and eventually lithified into sedimentary rock.": "",
  "Which process transforms sedimentary rock into metamorphic rock?": "",
  "Rapid melting of minerals deep within the mantle": "",
  "Slow cooling and crystallization from liquid magma": "",
  "Increased heat and pressure": "",
  "Chemical breakdown through acidic groundwater reactions": "",
  "When sedimentary rocks are buried deeply, the increased heat and pressure cause their minerals to recrystallize and reorganize without melting, creating metamorphic rock.": "",
  "Which pair of processes converts igneous rock to sedimentary rock?": "",
  "Weathering/erosion followed by compaction/cementation": "",
  "Subduction and uplift": "",
  "Melting and cooling": "",
  "Heat and pressure": "",
  "Igneous rock must first be broken down by weathering and erosion into sediments, then those sediments must be compacted and cemented together to form sedimentary rock.": "",
  "Subduction contributes to the rock cycle by:": "",
  "Forming fossils": "",
  "Pulling surface rocks into the mantle where they can melt": "",
  "Creating sedimentary layers": "",
  "Causing weathering at the surface": "",
  "At subduction zones, oceanic plates dive beneath other plates into the mantle, where rocks melt into magma that may later erupt and solidify as new igneous rock.": "",
  "Melting any rock produces:": "",
  "Fine sediment particles that are scattered by erosion": "",
  "Compressed fossil impressions preserved within layers": "",
  "Dense metamorphic rock containing foliated mineral bands": "",
  "Magma, which may cool to form igneous rock": "",
  "When any rock type melts, it becomes magma (or lava at the surface), and when that molten material cools and solidifies, it forms new igneous rock.": "",
  "Uplift is important in the rock cycle because it:": "",
  "Pushes rocks deeper underground where they eventually melt into magma": "",
  "Exposes deeply buried rocks to weathering and erosion at the surface": "",
  "Compresses organic sediment layers into economically valuable fossil fuels": "",
  "Increases confining pressure on buried rocks, triggering recrystallization": "",
  "Tectonic uplift raises buried rocks to Earth's surface, where they are exposed to wind, water, and ice, continuing the cycle through weathering and erosion.": "",
  "Cementation occurs when:": "",
  "Intense underground heat melts adjacent rock layers, fusing sediment into a solid mass": "",
  "Dissolved minerals crystallize between sediment grains, binding them together": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions deposit layers of ash that chemically bond with existing surface rock": "",
  "River currents carry mineral-rich sediment downstream and deposit it in a new basin area": "",
  "Minerals dissolved in groundwater precipitate between sediment particles, acting as natural glue to form solid sedimentary rock in the cementation stage of lithification.": "",
  "The fastest transformation in the rock cycle is typically:": "",
  "Volcanic eruption and lava cooling at the surface": "",
  "Deep burial metamorphism": "",
  "Slow underground magma cooling": "",
  "Lithification of deep ocean sediments": "",
  "Lava can cool and solidify into igneous rock in a matter of hours to days on Earth's surface, making it the fastest transformation, while processes like metamorphism can take millions of years.": "",
  "What is lithification?": "",
  "The melting of rocks into magma": "",
  "The process of turning loose sediments into solid sedimentary rock through compaction and cementation": "",
  "The cooling of lava into igneous rock": "",
  "The alignment of minerals under pressure": "",
  "Lithification is the process by which loose, unconsolidated sediments are transformed into solid sedimentary rock, primarily through the combined effects of compaction and cementation.": "",
  "What does 'weathering' mean in the rock cycle?": "",
  "The deposition of minerals from solution": "",
  "The movement of sediments by wind or water": "",
  "The heating of rock underground": "",
  "The physical and chemical breakdown of rock at or near Earth's surface into smaller pieces": "",
  "Weathering is the in-place breakdown of rock into smaller fragments through physical processes (frost wedging, root growth) and chemical processes (dissolution, oxidation) at or near Earth's surface.": "",
  "What does 'erosion' mean?": "",
  "The breakdown of rock in place": "",
  "The transport of weathered rock fragments and sediment by wind, water, ice, or gravity": "",
  "The formation of crystals in magma": "",
  "The compression of rock under pressure": "",
  "Erosion is the process by which weathered material (sediment) is picked up and transported from one location to another by agents such as water, wind, glaciers, or gravity.": "",
  "What does 'deposition' mean in the rock cycle?": "",
  "The laying down of sediment in a new location after being transported by water, wind, or ice": "",
  "The folding and buckling of rock layers under tectonic compression forces deep within the crust": "",
  "The slow cooling and solidification of magma within underground chambers to form crystalline rock": "",
  "The gradual melting of rock at depth due to rising temperatures near tectonic plate boundaries": "",
  "Deposition is the geological process where sediments, soil, and rock are added to a landform when the transporting agent (water, wind, or ice) loses energy and drops its load.": "",
  "What does 'compaction' mean in the context of sedimentary rock formation?": "",
  "The growth of crystals in magma": "",
  "The dissolving of minerals in water": "",
  "The breaking apart of rock by ice": "",
  "The squeezing together of sediment layers by the weight of overlying material, reducing pore space": "",
  "Compaction occurs when the weight of overlying sediment layers squeezes deeper layers together, forcing out water and air from pore spaces and reducing the volume of the sediment.": "",
  "What is crystallization in the rock cycle?": "",
  "The burial of fossils in sediment": "",
  "The process by which atoms in molten rock arrange into ordered crystal structures as the rock cools": "",
  "The breaking down of rock by weather": "",
  "The transport of sediment by rivers": "",
  "Crystallization occurs when magma or lava cools and the atoms organize into orderly mineral crystal structures, forming the interlocking grain texture characteristic of igneous rocks.": "",
  "What does 'recrystallization' mean in metamorphism?": "",
  "The formation of sediment from weathered rock": "",
  "The growth of new mineral crystals from magma": "",
  "The rearrangement and growth of mineral crystals within a solid rock due to heat and pressure without melting": "",
  "The dissolving of crystals in acid rain": "",
  "Recrystallization is the process during metamorphism where existing mineral crystals dissolve and regrow into new, often larger crystals without the rock melting, changing its texture and sometimes mineralogy.": "",
  "What is 'uplift' in the context of the rock cycle?": "",
  "The deposition of sediment in a river delta": "",
  "The tectonic process that pushes buried rocks upward toward Earth's surface, exposing them to weathering": "",
  "The melting of rock in the mantle": "",
  "The downward sinking of oceanic plates": "",
  "Uplift is the tectonic process that raises rocks from depth to the surface through forces like mountain building, fault movement, or isostatic rebound, exposing them to surface weathering.": "",
  "What does 'magma' mean?": "",
  "Molten rock found beneath Earth's surface that may contain dissolved gases and crystals": "",
  "Solid rock that has been compressed": "",
  "Sediment at the bottom of the ocean": "",
  "Water heated by underground rocks": "",
  "Magma is molten rock located beneath Earth's surface, typically containing dissolved gases and sometimes suspended crystals; when it reaches the surface through volcanic eruptions, it is called lava.": "",
  "What does 'sediment' mean?": "",
  "Crystallized mineral structures that form inside cooling magma chambers deep beneath the surface": "",
  "Small particles of rock, mineral, or organic material that have been weathered and transported": "",
  "The dense layer of liquid iron and nickel that circulates within Earth's outer core region": "",
  "Hot pressurized molten rock flowing beneath Earth's crust that may eventually erupt at volcanoes": "",
  "Sediment consists of fragments of rock, minerals, or biological material that have been broken down by weathering and transported by wind, water, ice, or gravity to a new location.": "",
  "A geologist finds limestone in the Himalayan Mountains at 5,000 meters elevation. She knows limestone forms on ocean floors. What rock cycle processes explain how marine sedimentary rock ended up at the top of a mountain?": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions launched the rock to that height": "",
  "The ocean level was once 5,000 meters higher": "",
  "The limestone was carried there by glaciers": "",
  "Tectonic uplift from the collision of the Indian and Eurasian plates pushed ancient sea-floor sedimentary rock to great heights": "",
  "The collision of the Indian and Eurasian plates created enormous compressive forces that uplifted ancient marine sedimentary rocks thousands of meters, demonstrating how tectonic uplift moves rocks through the cycle.": "",
  "A student visiting a volcanic island collects a sample of fresh lava that cooled overnight. Her teacher asks her to trace all the possible future paths this rock could take in the rock cycle. Which answer includes all possibilities?": "",
  "It can be weathered into sediment and become sedimentary rock, subjected to heat and pressure to become metamorphic rock, or re-melted into magma to form new igneous rock": "",
  "It can only return to the mantle through subduction where it re-melts into magma, since igneous rock lacks the mineral structure needed for metamorphic or sedimentary transformation": "",
  "It must first be broken down by weathering into sediments and lithified into sedimentary rock before any further transformations are possible within the rock cycle sequence": "",
  "Once igneous rock has fully cooled and its mineral crystals have locked into place, its composition becomes too stable for any further geological transformation to occur": "",
  "In the rock cycle, igneous rock can follow multiple paths: weathering and lithification into sedimentary rock, metamorphism into metamorphic rock, or re-melting back into magma.": "",
  "A farmer notices that the soil on her hillside field washes away during heavy rains, exposing bare rock. A conservation agent explains that vegetation removal has accelerated erosion. In the rock cycle, what happens to the washed-away sediment next?": "",
  "It is transported downhill and eventually deposited in lower areas, where it may be buried, compacted, and cemented into sedimentary rock over time": "",
  "It is subjected to extreme pressure as it moves downhill, undergoing rapid metamorphism from friction and compression to form new metamorphic rock formations": "",
  "It dissolves completely in acidic groundwater during transport and is permanently removed from the rock cycle without contributing to any new formation": "",
  "It is pushed deep underground through cracks in the bedrock where geothermal heat melts it into magma that will later solidify as igneous rock": "",
  "Eroded sediment is transported by water to lower elevations (rivers, lakes, oceans) where it is deposited and may eventually undergo compaction and cementation to become new sedimentary rock.": "",
  "A scientist studying a subduction zone observes that oceanic crust is being pulled deep into the mantle. She explains this is a critical step in the rock cycle. What happens to the rock as it descends into the mantle?": "",
  "The rock is vaporized by extreme mantle temperatures and the resulting gases escape through volcanic vents and fractures at the surface": "",
  "The intense mantle pressure crushes the descending rock into fine sediment particles that are eventually returned to the ocean floor": "",
  "The rock remains solid and chemically stable because temperatures at that depth in the mantle are not sufficient to alter its mineral structure": "",
  "The rock is heated, may undergo metamorphism, and eventually melts into magma that can rise and form new igneous rock": "",
  "As subducting rock descends, increasing temperature and pressure first metamorphose it, then melt it into magma, which can rise through the crust to erupt as lava, completing a major pathway of the rock cycle.": "",
  "A city engineer discovers that the foundation bedrock under a new building site is schist, a metamorphic rock. She traces its history: it was originally mud deposited in an ancient seabed. What sequence of rock cycle processes transformed ocean-floor mud into schist?": "",
  "Ocean-floor mud was directly compressed by tectonic forces into schist without passing through any intermediate sedimentary rock stage": "",
  "Erosion carried the mud deep underground where volcanic heat melted it into magma, which cooled and crystallized as the schist formation": "",
  "Deposition and lithification formed shale (sedimentary), then heat and pressure transformed the shale into schist (metamorphic)": "",
  "The mud was first melted by geothermal heat into magma, which then slowly cooled in a subsurface chamber to form crystalline schist rock": "",
  "The mud was first compacted and cemented into shale (a sedimentary rock), then tectonic forces subjected the shale to elevated heat and pressure, causing metamorphism into schist with aligned mica crystals.": "",
  "A student argues that the rock cycle takes millions of years, so it is not relevant to human timescales. Her teacher disagrees. Which example best shows the rock cycle operating on human-observable timescales?": "",
  "The lithification of deep ocean sediment": "",
  "A volcanic eruption producing new igneous rock that is immediately exposed to weathering": "",
  "The formation of metamorphic rock deep underground": "",
  "Continental drift moving plates 2 cm per year": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions produce new igneous rock in hours to days, and that rock immediately begins weathering, demonstrating that parts of the rock cycle are observable on human timescales.": "",
  "A mining company extracts marble from a quarry. A geologist explains that the marble was once a coral reef limestone that was buried and transformed. A new worker asks if the marble could ever return to being limestone. What is the correct response?": "",
  "Only if it is compressed again at the same depth": "",
  "Only if it melts first into magma": "",
  "Yes, if the marble is weathered into calcium carbonate sediment that is deposited and lithified, it could form new limestone": "",
  "No, metamorphic rocks can never become sedimentary again": "",
  "In the rock cycle, marble can be weathered and dissolved, and the calcium carbonate can be redeposited in water, eventually lithifying into new limestone, demonstrating the cycle's interconnected nature.": "",
  "A coastal town notices that cliff faces are rapidly eroding after a series of storms. A geologist explains that this erosion is part of the rock cycle. A town council member asks where the eroded material goes. What is the most accurate answer?": "",
  "It is carried out to sea as sediment, deposited on the ocean floor, and may eventually become new sedimentary rock": "",
  "It vanishes permanently from the geological record": "",
  "It melts into magma under the ocean": "",
  "It immediately turns back into the same type of rock": "",
  "Eroded cliff material is transported as sediment by waves and currents to the ocean floor, where it accumulates in layers and may eventually be compacted and cemented into new sedimentary rock.": "",
  "A geoscience professor shows her class a sandstone sample and asks them to describe every step needed to transform it back into magma through the rock cycle. Which sequence is correct?": "",
  "Sandstone undergoes weathering, then melts directly into magma": "",
  "Sandstone is dissolved in water, then the water evaporates into magma": "",
  "Sandstone must first become igneous rock before it can melt": "",
  "Sandstone is buried deeply, subjected to heat and pressure to become metamorphic rock, then heated further until it melts into magma": "",
  "Sandstone can be deeply buried by tectonic forces, experiencing increasing heat and pressure that first metamorphose it, and then, if temperatures rise enough, it melts completely into magma.": "",
  "A group of students is debating whether humans have any impact on the rock cycle. One student claims that human quarrying, mining, and construction are part of the rock cycle. Is this correct?": "",
  "No, humans have zero effect on geological processes": "",
  "Yes, humans accelerate weathering and erosion through mining, quarrying, and land clearing, but these impacts are small compared to natural geological forces": "",
  "No, the rock cycle only involves natural volcanic processes": "",
  "Yes, humans are the primary driver of the rock cycle": "",
  "Human activities like mining, quarrying, and deforestation do accelerate erosion and redistribute rock material, making us participants in the rock cycle, though our effects are tiny compared to natural processes operating over geologic time.": ""
